These are actually two different lines of spells (the cancel magic line and the strip enchantment line). This is how they work:<br>
<br>
Cancel magic (a spell 10 classes receive at one point or another) is the baseline. It has the potential to remove a single buff or magic-based debuff/DoT from your target. It can also be resisted.<br>
<br>
Nullify magic is the upgrade to cancel magic. It has the same effect as casting cancel magic twice (removes two buffs), plus it has a lower resist rate (it has the same resist rate as cancel magic, as if you were 4 levels higher than you actually are).<br>
<br>
Annul magic is the upgrade to nullify magic. It will remove two buffs and has an even lower resist rate (a nine level bonus).<br>
<br>
Strip enchantment (enchanter-only) is exactly the same as casting cancel magic four times, i.e. it has the potential to remove four buffs at once.<br>
<br>
Pillage enchantment is an upgrade to strip enchantment; it removes four buffs, but has a lower resist rate (a four level bonus).<br>
<br>
Recant magic is an upgrade to pillage enchantment; it removes four buffs, and has the lowest resist rate (a nine level bonus).<br>
<br>
<br>
End Quote.<br>
